    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Okay, I follow. So it's basically a competitive inhibition situation. Can you explain more about the difference in how it affects COX-1 versus COX-2? Since COX-1 is usually involved in protective functions like the stomach lining, does the binding mechanism itself explain why there's a difference in selectivity?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ibuprofen's differences in selectivity between COX-1 and COX-2 can be attributed to a combination of factors including binding affinity, steric hindrance, and the enzymes' respective active site topology. Although ibuprofen does indeed bind competitively to both COX-1 and COX-2, the slight differences in their active sites lead to differing degrees of binding efficiency.\n\nThe structure of COX-2 has more flexibility in its active site compared to COX-1, which offers a bit more space for the methylation of the hydrophobic lid of the active site that is carried out by the endogenous substrate 'Arachidonic Acid.' Ibuprofen's attempt to mimic this substrate 'locks' onto these regions, but the variance in the binding pocket allows for greater binding to COX-2. The additional affinity for COX-2 arises not just from structural differences but also from evolutionary adaptations that make COX-2 more accessible to antithrombotic drugs (like aspirin) in comparison to COX-1.\n\nTherefore, even though the mechanism of competitive inhibition remains the same – the drug molecules vie for the same binding location as the natural substrate – the actual interaction energy calculations, hydrogen bonding patterns, and ster",
      "source": "target",
